communicated by:
ProMED-SoAs from HealthMap Alerts
<promed-SoAs@promedmail.org>

[The timing of the outbreak appears to have been such that the incubation period was short. Knowing the incubation period, what symptoms were present (nausea, vomiting, diarrhea and/or non-gastrointestinal) and whether fever was present can help in the differential diagnosis. Knowing what foods were served can also help. For short incubation foodborne diseases, 2 most noteworthy are staphylococcal enterotoxin illness or heavy metal poisoning, the latter from ingesting liquids from containers that may leach the metal. Food contaminated with chemicals such as insecticides can also present with a short incubation illness.

Laghman is one of the 34 provinces of Afghanistan, located in the eastern part of the country. - Mod.LL

ProMED-mail would appreciate receiving clarification about this incident from informed sources. - Mod.SH

HealthMap/ProMED map available at:
